When using the confluence editor, the [ character can be used as a shortcut for page linking. Typing after the character will search page names for a suitable autocomplete. Using the arrow keys to choose the desired page and hitting enter will then complete the link.

However, there is additional functionality that the editor can understand by using the complete wiki markup syntax that begins with a left square bracket. That is, typing [link text|SPACE:Page Title] will create a link with the desired link text to a designated page title in the designated space. This is incredibly powerful, since you can to some degree design structure and naming of pages yet to be created inline in the editor, but the autocompletion tools do not work so well with it in the case of searching pages that already exist.

What I would like to see is the current behavior persist, up until the user types the pipe character. For everything after the pipe character, the autocomplete popup should search on that instead, including a space designation if present. I am attaching a screenshot that shows the present behavior. With this enhancement, the menu item would say "Search for 'Page Name'", and upon opening the search window, "link text" would be populated in the Link Text field, and the desired space key of SPACE would be the one being searched. If the page already existed in this space, then naturally that page would be presented as an option in the initial menu.

